==Notes pi référinches==
* Recueil de chansons et airs notés français, italiens et latins, composés par Guillaume DUFAY, Antoine BUSNOIS, Jean OKEGHEM, Firmin CARON et COMPÈRE - Vue 11 = Firmin CARON - Accueillie m’a la belle (Rondeau); Format : Parchemin. - 198 et 6 feuillets. - 180 × 120 mm. - Reliure parchemin - Source : Bibliothèque nationale de France, Département des manuscrits, Français 15123 - Date d'édition : 1401-1500
* David Fallows: "Firminus Caron", Grove Music Online, ed. L. Macy , [http://www.grovemusic.com (subscription access)]
* Gustave Reese, ''Music in the Renaissance''.  New York, W.W. Norton & Co., 1954.  ISBN 0-393-09530-4
* Thomson, J. Les Oeuvres Complètes de Philippe(?) Caron, Collected Works, VI/1 and 2, The Institute of Mediæval Music, Ltd., New York, vol. 1, 1971 and vol. 2, 1976.
* Marix, J. Histoire de la musique et des musiciens à la cour de Bourgogne sous le règne de Philippe le Bon, Strasbourg, 1939, pp. 193 ff. 
* Houdoy, J. Histoire artistique de la cathédrale de Cambrai, Lille, 1880, f. 83. 

* The Chansonnier cordiforme [SR] 1980: label (Caron) pamphlet, p. 15 ("Caron ... has so far eluded certain identification") - LC in RLIN, 6-24-88 (hdg.: Caron, Philippe, 15th cent.; usage: Philippe (?) Caron)
* New Grove, 2nd ed., WWW site, Feb. 2, 2001 (Caron, Firminus; fl. ca. 1460-1475; French composer; "the ascriptions for his music all read simply 'Caron' apart from 'F. Caron' in the case of the mass L'homme arme ... (assertions that it reads 'P. Caron' are definitely wrong; and it cannot stand for 'Filippo'))"
* New Grove (Caron, Philippe [Firmin], fl. 2nd half of the 15th century; both "Philippe" and "Firmin" given as forenames in contemporary documents)
* Thomson, J. An introduction to Philippe (?) Caron, c1964: p. 2 ("[T]here is no actual reason for the serious consideration of more than two possible first names: Firminus and Philippe") 

